In 1974, Richard Feynman stood before the graduating class at Caltech and apologized. He apologized on behalf of physics professors everywhere for never teaching students the scientific approach directly; for assuming they would absorb it by exposure to scientific work, the way islanders in the Pacific absorbed the forms of airport culture by watching planes land.1 Feynman was identifying a specific problem: the training pipeline for scientists does not explicitly teach the scientific approach, what this paper equates with epistemology following Popper’s own usage2, and as a result even honest, well-intentioned scientists end up practicing what Feynman called cargo cult science without realizing it, reproducing the surface forms of scientific inquiry without the epistemological substance that makes it genuine. But there is a second and related problem that compounds the first. K-12 teachers and education researchers who went through formal education programs encounter epistemology directly, but in a form that actively obscures rather than clarifies the foundation science education should rest on. Those programs treat Popper's epistemology as one voice among several equally valid options, giving teachers not an absent epistemological foundation but a confused one. Problem one produces scientists whose epistemological grounding, if they have it at all, was acquired through implicit modeling rather than explicit teaching, a weaker and less reliable mechanism that works for some but leaves most without the clear epistemological foundation that direct instruction would provide. Problem two produces teachers who teach content without epistemological grounding because they learned that no single epistemological foundation is correct. Both problems produce the same outcome, students who never explicitly learn the scientific approach, but through different mechanisms requiring different solutions. Fifty years after Feynman's apology, neither problem has been adequately addressed. But both share the same broad recognition as their solution, and this paper treats them as one fundamental problem and argues that Popperian epistemology, specifically falsificationism over justificationism, and the systems thinking tradition from Aristotle through Newton and Goldratt, supply the best available explanation of what Feynman was missing and why a tutoring approach built on that foundation is designed the way it is, while leaving the effectiveness of that approach to future empirical study. .  
The problem is visible in any survey of philosophy of education curricula. Epistemology sections predominantly list Popper alongside Kuhn, Lakatos, Feyerabend, and others as if the question of how science works remains genuinely open, as if there is no better and worse answer, only different perspectives, with notable exceptions that argue for greater Popperian influence but stop short of treating his framework as the best available foundation as currently understood.⁴ This is a mistake physics education does not make. We do not teach Aristotelian physics alongside Einsteinian relativity as equally valid current options. We teach Aristotle as a historically important predecessor whose ideas were refuted and replaced by theories that have survived all attempts at refutation so far. Notably, the tools used to correct Aristotle's justificationism, systems thinking, non-contradiction, and the demand for causal explanation over correlation, are tools Aristotle himself developed. The correction is internal to the tradition, not external to it, which is precisely what the Scientific Approach's self-correcting capacity predicts. Some questions get settled in exactly this way, not by proof or confirmation, but by criticism breaking the symmetry between positions.5 A single criticism pointing to a flaw in one position that is absent from its rival is sufficient to break that symmetry; there is no weighing of evidence involved, only the asymmetric elimination of the position that cannot survive the criticism. A tradition that has survived extensive rounds of criticism occupies a different epistemic position than a rival that has not yet been subjected to the same critical scrutiny; the tradition has earned its position through survival, not through accumulation of positive support. Popper's framework has survived decades of criticism from Kuhn, Lakatos, Feyerabend, and others, while justificationism has not recovered from the regress problem Popper identified. That asymmetry is the Popperian basis for treating them differently, not that one has more positive support than the other, but that one has an unrefuted criticism against it while the other does not. A position with an unrefuted criticism against it is not one voice among equals with a position that has no such criticism; the symmetry has been broken. The alternatives to Popper, Kuhn, Lakatos, Feyerabend, have been shown either to complement rather than defeat his core normative claim, or to rest on mischaracterizations of his actual position. Where genuine flaws have been identified within Popper's framework, as when later Popperians identified that his concept of critical preferences inadvertently smuggles in justificationist assumptions,5 the tradition has corrected them, demonstrating precisely the self-correcting capacity that Popper's epistemology prescribes. The asymmetry is not between a perfect Popperian framework and flawed alternatives, but between a self-correcting tradition that has survived and improved through criticism and a justificationist tradition that has not recovered from the regress problem Popper identified. Treating that asymmetry as if it doesn't exist is not intellectual balance but intellectual failure.6 A teacher who has learned that Popper is one interesting option among several has no clear epistemological foundation when deciding how to teach scientific reasoning. They default to teaching content, because content is less controversial, while the epistemological process remains implicit and unexamined, exactly the situation Feynman was describing.
That the debate appears unsettled in education curricula is partly explained by apparent conflicts between Popper and his successors that deserve direct examination. Many of these dissolve under scrutiny, while others identified genuine flaws that the Popperian tradition has since corrected, demonstrating the self-correcting capacity Popper's epistemology prescribes.7 His core normative claim is that knowledge-creation works by refutation not justification. Kuhn, for instance, argued that Popper attributed to science a linear, gradual convergence on final certain truth, and rejected this. But Popper never made that claim nor does his theory imply it. He prescribed a mechanism, bold conjecture exposed to rigorous criticism, not a pace or scale of change, and not convergence on a final destination. As Deutsch clarified, progress toward truth in Popper's framework means movement from more flawed theories to less flawed theories, a direction of travel not an arrival point.8 The conflict dissolves once Popper's actual position is read rather than the position attributed to him. Education curricula that treat the post-Popperian debate as leaving the normative question permanently open are inheriting mischaracterizations of Popper's actual position rather than resolving them, and leaving teachers without the epistemological foundation they need.
Popper did not invent a new method of science, but made explicit the critical structure underlying successful scientific practice, while also identifying and correcting systematic errors in how science is often conducted and taught. What teaching Popper correctly would change in practice begins with understanding what he corrected. Aristotle's justificationism, the idea dominant in Western thought for two thousand years that knowledge requires justification by other knowledge, produces an infinite regress with no resolution.9 Popper's replacement: knowledge requires not justification but refutation. A claim counts as knowledge not because it has been proven true by supporting evidence but because it has survived all attempts to show it false so far. The difference becomes vivid through a concrete example. Consider a murder trial. The prosecution presents a theory that the defendant committed the crime, supported by empirical evidence consistent with that theory. But the defense attorney doesn't need to prove the prosecution wrong directly; they only need to present a plausible alternative theory that is also consistent with the same empirical evidence. This works because evidence can only rule out theories; it cannot select a single theory from among all logically possible theories consistent with it. There are always infinitely many logically possible theories that agree with any given set of evidence, which is precisely why the defense only needs to present one plausible alternative theory consistent with the same evidence to undermine the prosecution's case; the prosecution's theory has not survived that criticism. That alone is sufficient to destroy the prosecution's case, because it demonstrates that the evidence was never as decisive as it appeared. Confirmation is meaningless. If a theory is consistent with all the empirical evidence, that does not imply that it's correct. Crucially, this asymmetry is not a matter of degree; a single criticism is sufficient to reject a theory, and there is no weighing involved. We cannot differentiate between rival theories by seeing which has fewer criticisms or more positive support and there are no weak or strong criticisms; doing so means accepting a contradiction, and it is the same pseudo-scientific move as attempting to calculate the probability that a theory is true rather than seeking the criticism that would refute it. A teacher who genuinely understands this teaches students to ask not "what evidence supports my theory?" but "what evidence would distinguish my theory from competing ones?" and “what alternative theories would also explain all the evidence?” They teach students that an explanation consistent with everything explains nothing. They teach students to trace causal mechanisms rather than accumulate correlations, because a correlation consistent with multiple causal theories does not help you select a theory from its rivals.
Popperian epistemology leads naturally to a further requirement that is implicit in his framework even though he didn't use this vocabulary explicitly. Science deals with systems, phenomena produced by causally interacting parts, and refuting a causal claim requires first understanding which parts of the system are relevant and how they interact. To refute a causal claim you must first identify what causal claim you are actually making, and that requires understanding how the parts of the system relate to each other causally. A correlation between two phenomena is consistent with multiple competing causal theories and therefore refutes none of them. The correct question is not "does this observation fit my theory?" but "what is the causal mechanism connecting these parts of the system, and at what level does the root cause operate?" This requirement places qualitative reasoning prior to quantitative reasoning; you must first understand what system you are in and what causal claim you are making before any quantitative analysis can be meaningfully applied. This is systems thinking; tracing causal relationships between the parts of a system to identify the constraint generating the problem at its deepest level rather than stopping at a surface correlation or a symptom. Systems thinking is one important tool within the broader scientific approach, applied when causal structure is obscured by interacting parts, confounds, or emergent behavior, not a universal requirement for every scientific task. Systems thinking, as used here, refers specifically to identifying the level and structure of interacting components necessary to distinguish competing explanations, a step often omitted when reasoning remains at the level of surface descriptions or correlations. This requirement is implicit in Popper's own framework: a genuinely falsifiable causal mechanism cannot be identified without first understanding which components of the system are causally relevant and how they interact. Goldratt made this vocabulary explicit, but the requirement is already implicit in Popper.10 Achieving genuine explanatory depth, the kind Popper's framework demands, where an explanation must identify a falsifiable causal mechanism rather than merely establish a causal relationship, requires systems thinking, because identifying the mechanism requires understanding how the parts of the system interact causally at the level where the root cause operates. Basic causal identification through controlled intervention is possible without systems thinking, but it produces only the first step of a genuine scientific explanation.
The following example illustrates what these consequences can look like in practice, drawn from the author's oral examination of premed students using Socratic questioning.11 The most common reasoning failure encountered is not factual ignorance; students can reproduce correct answers. It is the inability to explain the causal mechanism one level below the emergent property being described. This is one illustration of a broader pattern; students trained without explicit epistemological grounding exhibit a range of reasoning failures that share the same root cause, of which the correlation-causation confusion discussed below is another example. Asked why oxygen moves from the lungs into the bloodstream, a student will say 'because of diffusion.' Asked to explain what diffusion is and why it happens, the same student will often say 'it's when molecules move from high concentration to low concentration', and consider the question answered. That second answer sounds like a real definition because it is correct. But it is a redescription of the observation, not an explanation of the mechanism that produces it. The word 'diffusion' sounds like an explanation because it is a technical term, and 'molecules move from high concentration to low concentration' sounds like a definition because it is accurate, but neither identifies the causal mechanism that generates the phenomenon. The actual mechanism, that molecules are in constant random motion, that the concentration gradient means more collisions occur in the direction of lower concentration, and that this asymmetry in collision frequency produces net directional movement, is precisely what both answers omit. They have not learned that explanation requires identifying the mechanism, not just restating the phenomenon at a slightly more abstract level or attaching a technical label to it. This pattern is consistent with science education that teaches conclusions without teaching the epistemological standard that distinguishes a genuine explanation from a redescription.  A student who understands Popper's framework, that an explanation must identify a falsifiable causal mechanism, would know that their answer was incomplete and would know what completing it requires. The same failure appears in how many students handle correlation and causation. They know the phrase as a slogan. They do not reliably apply it as a reasoning tool, because they have never learned the Popperian reason it matters; a correlation without a causal mechanism is an unfalsifiable just-so story, consistent with multiple competing theories and therefore does not help us select a theory from its rivals. Teaching the Scientific Approach does not mean transmitting Popper's framework as settled doctrine; it means creating conditions where students subject their own existing knowledge to the same conjecture and criticism the framework describes, a distinction developed more fully in subsequent work.  
When students trained without explicit epistemological grounding become physicians, the same reasoning failures operate at a larger scale with more serious consequences. The American Medical Association has acknowledged that physicians are traditionally trained to see relationships between the parts of the system with which they are directly involved but not necessarily to see the less-apparent systemic forces, and has identified systems thinking as an emerging third pillar of medical education precisely because it was previously absent from training.12
Feynman establishes that the scientific approach is not being taught explicitly and that this produces scientists who practice cargo cult science without realizing it. Popper establishes what the scientific approach consists of at the epistemological level, falsificationism over justificationism, causal mechanisms over correlations. The systems thinking dimension, tracing causal relationships between parts of a system to identify root causes, traces back to Aristotle and Newton, with Goldratt making explicit its application to goal-directed systems through the constraint concept. The framework described here requires more than procedural compliance to function as genuine science rather than cargo cult science. Feynman identified utter honesty, bending over backwards to show how you might be wrong, as the essential ingredient that cargo cult scientists lack. But honesty of that kind doesn't come without curiosity. A person who isn't genuinely curious about how things actually work has no strong motivation to pay the psychological cost of being honest about disconfirming evidence. Curiosity is the disposition that makes genuine honesty possible, and genuine honesty is what makes the framework function as science rather than its surface imitation. Part of the teacher's job is therefore not merely to transmit the framework but to generate genuine curiosity in students, curiosity being the motivational foundation without which the framework becomes cargo cult science. The oral examination evidence presented here suggests that the absence of explicit epistemological grounding produces specific and identifiable reasoning failures in students. Whether teaching the scientific approach explicitly produces measurable improvements in reasoning and downstream outcomes is the hypothesis this paper proposes for future empirical study.
The analysis in this paper establishes that the Scientific Approach needs to be taught explicitly rather than assumed to be absorbed by osmosis, and that this requires deliberate curricular attention at multiple levels of education. What explicit instruction in the Scientific Approach should look like in practice, how it should be sequenced within existing degree programs, what it should contain at introductory versus advanced levels, what teacher training it requires, and how its outcomes should be measured, are questions that demand educational research expertise beyond the scope of this epistemological argument. A full account of what the Scientific Approach as a teachable framework consists of at the level of its domain-general principles, is beyond the scope of this paper and is the necessary subject of subsequent work, recognizing that each discipline will develop its own domain-specific sub-methods in response to its particular challenges, as medicine developed the double blind experiment to address confounds that don't arise in the same form in other fields.13 
The epistemological confusion this paper identifies is not a minor academic oversight. It has consequences that reach from philosophy seminars all the way into the clinic, where physicians trained without explicit epistemological grounding make reasoning errors that cost patients their lives. A teacher who has learned that Popper is one voice among equals cannot teach Popperian reasoning as the best available foundation for scientific thinking. A professor who doesn't clearly understand the difference between refutation and justificationism cannot make that difference explicit in their teaching. Resolving that confusion requires education curricula to make a distinction they currently avoid, between epistemological questions that remain genuinely open and those that have been refuted and replaced by better frameworks. Popper's core insights belong in the second category. Treating them as belonging in the first has real costs, measured not in philosophical imprecision but in patient outcomes, in students who cannot distinguish explanation from redescription, and in entire subfields of science that spend decades accumulating confirming evidence for theories whose root causes they never correctly identified. That neither problem has been adequately addressed in the fifty years since Feynman's apology demands a deeper explanation than mere oversight. The persistence of this problem has both institutional and psychological dimensions; the psychological is addressed briefly here, the institutional is addressed in subsequent work. An education system built on justificationist assumptions produces students who seek confirmation rather than refutation, who experience criticism as threat rather than opportunity, and who therefore resist the very framework that would correct their approach. The institutional factors underlying this persistence, including deliberate design choices about what gets taught and what gets excluded, are beyond the scope of this paper and are addressed in subsequent work. It is among the most fundamental levers available for improving how the next generation of scientists, physicians, and thinkers actually reason, and it begins with taking seriously what Feynman was asking for fifty years ago.
