Feynman, R.P. "Cargo Cult Science." Caltech's commencement address, June 1974. Published in Engineering and Science, Vol. 37, No. 7, June 1974, pp. 10–13. Archived at the Caltech digital library: https://calteches.library.caltech.edu/51/2/CargoCult.pdf. The paper's references to Feynman's apology and to the cargo cult analogy draw directly from this speech. Readers are encouraged to read it in full; it remains one of the most precise accounts of what distinguishes genuine scientific reasoning from its surface imitation.
The equation between epistemology and the scientific approach is not an arbitrary terminological choice. Popper's original German title for what English speakers know as The Logic of Scientific Discovery was Logik der Forschung: Zur Erkenntnistheorie der modernen Naturwissenschaft, literally "Logic of Research: On the Epistemology of Modern Natural Science." Popper himself was treating epistemology and the scientific approach as the same inquiry. Furthermore, Popper explicitly held that rationality is not restricted to empirical or scientific theories but is a special case of the general method of criticism, finding and eliminating contradictions in knowledge, applicable to metaphysical ideas, moral values, and all domains of human inquiry. This paper follows Popper's own usage: epistemology, the scientific approach, and reason, properly understood, are the same fundamental activity applied to different domains. A full account of this equation and its implications is developed in subsequent work.
The author notes that several core elements of this framework, including the principle that all knowledge is connected and transferable across domains, were arrived at independently before encountering Popper, Deutsch, or related thinkers, documented in a dated unpublished article from 2011. Similarly, Popper and Goldratt never engaged with each other's work despite independently developing compatible frameworks; Popper's epistemology of conjecture and criticism and Goldratt's scientific approach to organizations are mutually consistent and mutually reinforcing, yet neither thinker appears to have read or responded to the other. All three drew from the same ancient tradition of Socrates and Aristotle, but the specific syntheses and extensions each developed were arrived at independently. Independent arrival at compatible syntheses from the same foundational tradition but through different intellectual paths refutes the specific hypothesis that the framework developed here is merely one person's idiosyncratic intellectual construction, though it does not by itself establish the framework's correctness, which must be evaluated on the merits of the arguments presented in this paper. 
Notable exceptions exist in the literature that argue for greater Popperian influence in science education. Matthews, Michael R. Science Teaching: The Role of History and Philosophy of Science. New York: Routledge, 1994, pp. 83-86. Matthews calls for increased involvement of philosophers of science in science education and cites Popper explicitly as a resource for developing students' understanding of scientific method, noting that the neglect of history and philosophy of science in education is in marked contrast to the expanding studies in philosophy of science itself. More recently, a Popperian approach to education has been explicitly defended on the grounds that refutationist epistemology carries profound implications for both politics and education, arguing that Popper's framework should inform educational aims, curriculum, and pedagogy (ERIC, EJ1190995, 2013). These contributions are significant and compatible with this paper's argument. However, they stop short of the stronger claim made here, that Popper's epistemology is not merely one valuable resource among others but the best available normative foundation for science education as currently understood, and that treating it otherwise has specific and measurable consequences. The dominant pattern in philosophy of education curricula remains the false equivalence this paper diagnoses, even among scholars sympathetic to Popper's contributions.
The criticism-breaks-symmetry principle used in this paper represents a correction of Popper's own concept of critical preferences, in which Popper suggested that in light of criticism we can prefer some theories to others as a matter of degree. Temple, Elliot, argues that this introduces justificationism through the back door — allowing degrees of goodness to substitute for decisive refutation. Temple proposes instead that ideas should be evaluated in a binary way as non-refuted or refuted. A single decisive criticism is sufficient to refute an idea. When two rival theories each fail to explain why they are better than the other, both are refuted by that failure — the symmetry between them is broken only when a criticism points to a flaw in one that is absent from the other, not by weighing which theory has more support or fewer criticisms against it. This paper follows Temple's correction. See: Temple, Elliot. "Arguments Should Be Decisive Criticisms." Critical Fallibilism, n.d. Available at: https://criticalfallibilism.com/arguments-should-be-decisive-criticisms/ and Temple, Elliot. "Introduction to Critical Fallibilism." Critical Fallibilism, n.d. Available at: https://criticalfallibilism.com/introduction-to-critical-fallibilism/
The false equivalence this paper diagnoses is not merely a theoretical concern. It has been documented in actual course practice. Stadler, Friedrich and Miles MacLeod, in their review of Stefano Gattei's Karl Popper's Philosophy of Science: Rationality Without Foundations, document that courses actively teach Popper as having failed rather than treating him as one voice among equals, which is worse than false equivalence. It is false hierarchy in the wrong direction. More significantly for this paper's argument, the reviewers note that Kuhn's philosophy, despite its reputation as a more sophisticated alternative to Popper, remains committed to foundationalist tenets that Popper genuinely abandons. Kuhn, unlike Popper, does not fully sever the connection between rationality and justification. This inverts the common curriculum treatment: the framework education programs typically present as having superseded Popper is itself more justificationist than the framework it claims to supersede. Stadler, Friedrich and Miles MacLeod. "Review of Karl Popper's Philosophy of Science: Rationality Without Foundations, by Stefano Gattei." Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews, 2009. Available at: https://ndpr.nd.edu/reviews/karl-popper-s-philosophy-of-science-rationality-without-foundations/
The most prominent example is Kuhn's paradigm shift model, often presented as contradicting Popper's epistemology. Kuhn, Thomas S. The Structure of Scientific Revolutions. University of Chicago Press, 1962. Kuhn raised several objections. First, he argued that scientists spend most of their time in "normal science", solving puzzles within an established paradigm, rather than constantly trying to refute fundamental theories. This is a valid historical observation but it operates at the descriptive level, not the normative one. Popper was prescribing what scientists should do to generate knowledge, not describing what they always do in practice. The gap between the two is real but it doesn't defeat Popper's normative claim; it identifies a systematic human tendency to resist refutation that Popper's framework correctly diagnoses as a problem. Second, Kuhn argued that some dogmatic commitment to a paradigm is productive; it allows scientists to go deep rather than constantly questioning foundations. But provisional practical commitment to a framework for purposes of productive inquiry is different from treating that framework as unfalsifiable in principle. A scientist can work within a paradigm while remaining open to its refutation; that is pragmatic efficiency, not dogmatism, and it is fully compatible with Popperian epistemology. Third, Kuhn argued that scientists don't immediately abandon theories when contradictory evidence appears, which he presented as contradicting Popper's logic. But Popper never required immediate theory abandonment upon encountering a single anomaly, nor does his theory imply it; he argued that persistence in the face of refuting evidence, and deliberate insulation of a theory from genuine attempts at refutation, are what constitute irrational dogmatism. A single anomaly is not automatically a refutation. Fourth, Kuhn argued that different paradigms are incommensurable, so different that rational comparison between them is impossible. The historical evidence contradicts this directly. Einstein did not discard Newton but revealed its boundary conditions and incorporated it as a special case, which is precisely commensurable comparison; we can identify exactly where Newton's predictions match Einstein's and where they diverge. As Deutsch clarified, Popper's progress toward truth means from more flawed to less flawed theory, not convergence on a final destination, which Kuhn's own position does not actually contradict. The consistent pattern across Kuhn's objections is that they either operate at the descriptive level while Popper's claim is normative, or they rest on mischaracterizations of Popper's actual position. Alternative accounts such as Kuhn's raise important observations about scientific practice, but these do not undermine Popper's normative account; rather, they highlight the ways in which actual scientific behavior often departs from the conditions required for effective error correction. Popper's framework has also been refined and corrected by Popperians themselves, demonstrating that the tradition is self-correcting in exactly the way Popper's epistemology predicts it should be. A comprehensive defense of Popper's epistemology against the full range of objections in the post-Popperian literature is beyond the scope of this paper and unnecessary; that work has already been done thoroughly by Popper himself and by later Popperians. Readers seeking that defense are directed to Popper's The Logic of Scientific Discovery and Conjectures and Refutations, and to Deutsch's The Fabric of Reality and The Beginning of Infinity.
Deutsch develops this clarification of Popper's notion of progress toward truth in The Beginning of Infinity (2011). The key point is that "closer to the truth" does not mean convergence on a final certain truth, which would reintroduce justificationism through the back door, but rather movement from theories with more flaws to theories with fewer flaws, through the mechanism of conjecture and criticism. Each theory that survives rigorous attempts at refutation is less wrong than the one it replaced, without being final or certain. This is a crucial clarification because the most common misreading of Popper, including Kuhn's, attributes to him a naive convergence on final truth that he never held and his theory does not imply. Deutsch's formulation makes Popper's actual position precise and immune to that misreading. Readers are directed to The Beginning of Infinity for the full development of this and related clarifications of Popperian epistemology. It is also worth noting, from the same work, that the popular understanding of Popperian refutation of empirical theories as requiring empirical evidence is itself a misreading. Deutsch argues that the vast majority of scientific theories are refuted by philosophical criticism rather than empirical evidence; most theories never survive long enough to be tested empirically because logical and philosophical criticism eliminates them first. Refutation through decisive criticism, whether empirical or philosophical, is the mechanism. The empirical case is a special instance, not the defining one.
Popper traces the dominance of justificationism, the view that knowledge requires proof or justification, explicitly in Conjectures and Refutations: The Growth of Scientific Knowledge (Routledge, 1963), where he notes that for centuries knowledge meant proven knowledge, proven either by the power of the intellect or by the evidence of the senses, and that this assumption had gone largely unchallenged for more than two thousand years despite early skeptical objections. Popper's identification of justificationism as a pervasive and long-standing philosophical error is developed throughout that volume and also in Objective Knowledge: An Evolutionary Approach (Oxford University Press, 1972). The attribution of justificationism specifically to Aristotle requires clarification; Aristotle was not the only source of justificationist thinking in Western philosophy, but his account of demonstrative knowledge in the Posterior Analytics, which held that genuine knowledge requires demonstration from first principles, established an influential template that shaped Western epistemology for centuries. Popper's critique targets the tradition broadly rather than Aristotle exclusively.
Early recognition that systems cannot be understood purely by analyzing isolated parts can be traced to Aristotle, whose observation that the whole is more than the sum of its parts established the foundational insight that a system's behavior cannot be understood by analyzing its parts in isolation. Aristotle. Metaphysics. Book H, 1045a. Translated by W.D. Ross. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1924. Though modern systems thinking develops this into a methodological framework, the core insight is ancient. According to Goldratt, in his lecture series the Goldratt Satellite Program (GSP), Newton observed that as the number of causal relationships between parts of a system increases, the number of parts governing the system decreases. Goldratt further argued that in goal-directed systems with sufficient causal relationships between parts, performance becomes dominated by a single element, the constraint, the general concept underlying what chemistry calls the limiting factor and engineering calls the bottleneck. In relatively stable goal-directed systems, this constraint can remain consistent long enough to be identified and optimized. In more complex or dynamic systems, different constraints may dominate at different times, however, at any given moment relative to a specific goal, one constraint functions as the most limiting factor and therefore as the governing element for decision-making. Whether this specific verbal formulation, that the limit reaches exactly one governing part, is an explicit claim by Lagrange or Goldratt's own interpretation of Lagrange's mathematics is not verified by the author of this paper. Goldratt's contribution was not inventing these concepts but synthesizing them into a coherent, explicit, teachable framework for organizational improvement, applying what he explicitly described as the scientific approach to organizations. This synthesis is developed across several works, most formally in The Theory of Constraints (North River Press, 1990) and narratively in The Goal: A Process of Ongoing Improvement (North River Press, 1984), co-authored with Jeff Cox. The paper's claim that this vocabulary is implicit in Popper's falsificationism rather than a separate contribution is the author's own synthesis and is developed more fully in subsequent work.
The observations reported here regarding premed students' reasoning failures are based on the author's direct tutoring practice using Socratic oral examination, and should be understood as anecdotal rather than as findings from a formal empirical study. The consistent pattern described, students giving conclusions without explaining the causal mechanism one level below the emergent property, has been observed across multiple students over several years of practice, but has not yet been subjected to systematic data collection, controlled conditions, or statistical analysis. A formal empirical study of this tutoring method, its implementation, and its outcomes is the subject of subsequent work. The author acknowledges that anecdotal observations, however consistent, are subject to confirmation bias and other limitations that only a rigorous study can address. Readers are encouraged to treat these observations as a source of hypotheses to be tested rather than as established findings.
The claim that physicians lack systems thinking due to absent epistemological training is consistent with mainstream medical sources. The American Medical Association explicitly acknowledges that physicians are traditionally trained to see relationships between the parts of the system with which they are directly involved but not the less-apparent systemic forces, and identifies systems thinking as an emerging third pillar of medical education that complements basic and clinical sciences, emerging precisely because it was previously absent. Gonzalo, Jed D. and Stephanie R. Starr. "How Can the Master Adaptive Learner Model and Health Systems Science Collaborate to Improve Health Care?" Chapter 15 in Cutrer, William B., Martin V. Pusic, Larry D. Gruppen, Maya M. Hammoud, and Sally A. Santen, eds. The Master Adaptive Learner. Chicago: American Medical Association, 2020. The specific claim about physicians being traditionally trained to see only their part of the system rather than broader systemic forces is drawn from this chapter as reported in "Why systems thinking is make or break for medical students' careers." American Medical Association, May 21, 2021. Available at: https://www.ama-assn.org/education/accelerating-change-medical-education/why-systems-thinking-make-or-break-medical-students. The author has not read the primary chapter directly and relies on this secondary source for the specific claim. 
The tutoring approach that motivates this paper, to be described fully in the second paper in this series, converges in important ways with two influential traditions in education research. Dewey's progressive education framework argued that effective learning requires active engagement with genuine problems rather than passive reception of content, and that the teacher's role is to create conditions for inquiry rather than transmit correct answers. Dewey, John. Experience and Education. New York: Macmillan, 1938. Vygotsky's zone of proximal development model argued that effective teaching operates in the gap between what a learner can do alone and what they can do with guidance; the teacher identifies exactly where understanding breaks down and works there. Vygotsky, L.S. Mind in Society: The Development of Higher Psychological Processes. Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1978. The tutoring approach described in the second paper is consistent with both frameworks, particularly in treating students as people who already possess relevant knowledge in both explicit and intuitive forms, with the teacher's job being to help them surface, connect, and subject that knowledge to criticism rather than fill an empty vessel. The approach also requires interpersonal conditions that progressive education theory, including Dewey, has long recognized, non-coercion and the student's voluntary engagement, but the Popperian framework supplies a more precise epistemological argument for why these conditions are necessary: fear and humiliation corrupt the feedback loops that genuine inquiry depends on, making anti-coercion and kindness not merely pedagogically preferable but epistemologically required. These conditions are addressed fully in the second paper in this series. This paper argues, however, that neither Dewey nor Vygotsky provides a sufficiently rigorous epistemological account of what makes inquiry genuine rather than merely active; Popper's epistemology, including the corrections explained in this paper, explains not just how learning should be structured but what the content of good scientific reasoning actually is. The full comparison between this framework and progressive and constructivist education traditions is developed in the second paper in this series.
